The Grasshopper Years of Latin America
The bad news continues to accumulate these days in Latin America.
Economic conditions are deteriorating almost everywhere, social cohesion is unraveling, and political instability is growing.
It's hardly surprising since the majority of Latin American countries have spent the last twenty years going nowhere.
The capital has been sold and national debts have been dramatically increased, but nothing lasting and beneficial has been achieved.
These years have really been eaten by grasshoppers.
Over the last 20 years, the annual growth rate of per capita GDP in Latin America has averaged 0.35%.
At this rate, an economy would take 200 years to double.
In Asia, the standard of living doubles every decade.
With such anemic growth, how can Latin America hope to compete in global trade except through a consistently timid rise in wages?
The economic stagnation is the responsibility of bad government, not bad luck.
If Latin America does not change, it may begin to look more and more like Africa - a region composed of weak states with large informal economies and widespread poverty.
Four factors have placed it on this path.
First, in the rush toward privatization, everything from public services to manufacturing industries has been auctioned off.
For a brief moment, the sale of capital helped balance national budgets and also provided resources to support consumption.
Finally, revenues from privatization have yielded little in terms of better infrastructure or more competitive exports.
Worse still, the liquidation of state assets was accompanied by massive external borrowing.
In some cases, notably in Argentina, the borrowing by domestic buyers exhausted all available credit ranges.
Other countries have not fallen to Argentina's level, but solvency represents a problem in almost all Latin American countries.
Secondly, since the reform did not bring prosperity, the region has become disillusioned with it.
The inflow of capital produced a wealth effect, but only as long as they existed.
When the money stopped flowing, the wealth dried up.
No sensible politician would embark on another decade of structural reforms that would test the patience of average Latin Americans beyond the limits of electoral survival.
But without a greater number of deep reforms, too few prerequisites for economic growth will be met to attract investments, without which no growth is possible.
This development dilemma announces the third factor: incompetent policies.
Governments that operated along technocratic lines and viewed economic growth as a rising tide that lifts all boats have disappeared.
In Argentina, clumsy presidents succeed one another.
Institutions are being dismantled, property rights are being called into question, and a more corrupt and random redistribution effort is underway.
Peru and Venezuela have little more chance; Brazil may soon follow the same path.
The popularity of Lula Ignacia da Silva and his team, who are leading opinion polls in the period preceding the Brazilian presidential elections, indicates that a large part of the Latin American population is prepared to reject traditional governments.
Lula and his party are so far from the dominant economic and political thinking that capital has already begun to flee - even though the elections are only a few months away.
In Mexico, democratization has brought greater stability, but this could well prove to be temporary.
The peso is now excessively overvalued.
If the external balance deteriorates further, the economy risks a hard landing.
As for all the good news about Mexico's emerging democracy, its president is beginning to justify the fears that existed about it: no vision, no Congress, and no team knowing what it has to do.
The last factor concerns the desperately low savings rate that is endemic to the Americas.
Indeed, this is the economic financial result, for where there is little savings, there is little investment—and little foundation to accumulate capital and increase productivity.
Venezuela now longs for the fat 1970s of OPEC -- which it did not participate in, having neglected to develop its oil industry.
The wealth of Argentina is now on vacation in Miami, perhaps for good.
Brazil and Mexico constitute perfect examples of countries that have sold their assets and borrowed rather than saved.
The contrast with Asia is striking.
Take China, where savings and investment rates reach almost 40%, where the current account is in surplus, and where there is no public debt.
Government institutions favor the market and the population is well-educated, disciplined, and flexible in its learning.
The rewards for taking risks and initiative are immediate and highly motivating.
One cannot deny that China remains a poor country.
Its per capita GDP is only half that of Brazil.
But with a growth rate in China's coastal region of about 15% per year, who can seriously doubt that within the next 15 years it will surpass Brazil?
In China, despite all the enormous problems encountered, things continue to go smoothly, first of all due to the massive inflow of foreign direct investments and the imminent benefits of joining the WTO.
In Latin America, things continue to fall apart: governments are backtracking on reform and the economy is losing ground compared to the rest of the world.
Latin America was doing well when unregulated funds were flowing in, but those times are largely gone.
We must therefore expect much worse economic, social, and political news in the years to come.
Demagogues such as Hugo Chavez in Venezuela or Carlos Menem -- an Argentine presidential candidate once again -- may resemble a bad joke, but anyone who cares about the fate of Latin America should not laugh at it.
